'''Zareh Sinanyan''' (born 1974) is the current mayor of [[Glendale, California|Glendale]], [[California]]. Prior to being appointed mayor, he won election as a city councilman and held posts in various commissions, including Parks, Recreation and Community Service, and the Community Development Block Grant Advisory Committee.

==Early life and education==
Zareh Sinanyan was born in [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]], in 1974 and attended the local school No. 172.<ref name=asbarez>{{cite news|title=Sinanyan to Run for Glendale City Council|url=http://asbarez.com/107510/sinanyan-to-run-for-glendale-city-council/|newspaper=[[Asbarez]]|date=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=kelly>{{cite news|last1=Corrigan|first1=Kelly|title=Third graders get a visit from the mayor|agency=McClatchy - Tribune Business News|date=4 October 2014}}</ref> His father was born in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]] and settled in Armenia in 1946.<ref name=zarehsource /> His mother is from [[Talin]].<ref name=zarehsource>{{cite news|title=<U+00AB><U+0553><U+0578><U+057D><U+056B><U+00BB> <U+0561><U+0576><U+0563><U+056C><U+056B><U+0561><U+056F><U+0561><U+0576> <U+0564><U+057A><U+0580><U+0578><U+0581><U+056B><U+0581> <U+0574><U+056B><U+0576><U+0579><U+0565><U+0582> <U+0533><U+056C><U+0565><U+0576><U+0564><U+0565><U+056C><U+056B> <U+0584><U+0561><U+0572><U+0561><U+0584><U+0561><U+057A><U+0565><U+057F><U+0561><U+0580><U+0561><U+0576>. <U+0570><U+0561><U+0580><U+0581><U+0561><U+0566><U+0580><U+0578><U+0582><U+0575><U+0581> <U+0576><U+0578><U+0580><U+0561><U+0576><U+0577><U+0561><U+0576><U+0561><U+056F> <U+0584><U+0561><U+0572><U+0561><U+0584><U+0561><U+057A><U+0565><U+057F> <U+0536><U+0561><U+0580><U+0565><U+0570> <U+054D><U+056B><U+0576><U+0561><U+0576><U+0575><U+0561><U+0576><U+056B> <U+0570><U+0565><U+057F> (English: From Yerevan's "Posi" English school to mayor's office of Glendale. An interview with mayor of Glendale Zareh Sinanyan.|url=http://www.resource.am/arm/133842.html|agency=Resource.am|date=13 April 2014}}</ref>

He and his family immigrated to the United States in 1988 and settled in [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], California.<ref name=asbarez /> Sinanyan attended the [[John Muir Middle School (Burbank, California)|John Muir Middle School]] in Burbank and went on to graduate from [[Burbank High School (Burbank, California)|Burbank High School]].<ref name=kelly /> In 1997 he earned a Bachelor's Degrees in Political Science and History in 1997  at [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=mayor>{{cite web|title=Mayor Zareh Sinanyan|url=http://www.glendaleca.gov/government/city-council/councilmember-zareh-sinanyan|publisher=City of Glendale}}</ref><ref name=votez>{{cite web|title=Meet your next Glendale City Council Member|url=http://www.votezareh.com/about_zareh|website=Vote Zareh}}</ref> He then attended law school at the [[University of Southern California]], where he obtained his [[Juris Doctor]].<ref name=mayor /> While in law school, Sinanyan worked for the [[United States Securities and Exchange Commission]] and interned for Justice Earl Johnson of the California Court of Appeal.<ref name=votez /> After his graduation from law school, he entered civil litigation service and ran his own law office.<ref name=votez />

==Political career==
Sinanyan was appointed to the Parks, Recreation and Community Service's Commission of Glendale in 2006 and held this position until 2008.<ref name=votez /><ref name=mayor /> He served as chairman to the Community Development Block Grant Advisory Committee from 2009 to 2011.<ref name=mayor /> He was also a commissioner to the Community Development Block Grant Advisory Committee from  2008 to 2013.<ref name=mayor />

===City Councilman===
Sinanyan ran for one of three Glendale City Council seats in the April 2013 election and finished third out of twelve candidates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/20130403/glendale-council-candidate-zareh-sinanyan-accused-of-posting-slurs-among-top-finishers|title=Glendale council candidate Zareh Sinanyan, accused of posting slurs, among top finishers|first=Mariecar|last=Mendoza|date=2 April 2013|accessdate=17 December 2014|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]}}</ref> He is the first Armenian-born politician to hold a seat on the Glendale City Council.<ref>{{cite news|title=Glendale Mayor Zareh Sinanyan Visits the Western Diocese|url=http://www.armenianchurchwd.com/news/glendale-mayor-zareh-sinanyan-visits-the-western-diocese/|agency=Western Diocese of the Armenian Church|date=22 May 2014}}</ref> At his second City Council meeting, he publicly apologized for "racial and homophobic slurs" he had posted online for several years before the election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130502/glendale-councilman-zareh-sinanyan-apologizes-for-online-slurs|title=Glendale councilman Zareh Sinanyan apologizes for online slurs|first=Mariecar|last=Mendoza|date=1 May 2013|accessdate=17 December 2014|work=Los Angeles Daily News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2013/05/01/glendale-city-councilman-apologizes-for-past-racist-homophobic-vulgar-comments/|title=Glendale City Councilman Apologizes For Past Racist, Homophobic, Vulgar Comments|date=1 May 2013|accessdate=17 December 2014|work=CBS Los Angeles}}</ref>

In July 2013 Sinanyan supported the establishment of a memorial to Korean [[comfort women]] in the Glendale Central Park, over the objections of the government of Japan and dozens of Japanese-Americans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130709/glendale-approves-controversial-comfort-women-memorial|title=Glendale approves controversial 'comfort women' memorial|first=Christina|last=Villacorte|date=8 July 2013|accessdate=17 December 2014|work=Los Angeles Daily News}}</ref> Sinanyan spoke at the unveiling of the memorial in late July, citing his own background as the grandson of an [[Armenian Genocide]] survivor and asserting: "The best way to resolve conflicts...the best way to heal wounds...is to acknowledge them. My people, my
grandfather, were subjected to a horrible, horrible crime...To this day, because no apology has
come, no proper acknowledgement has come...the wound is deep, it's festering, and there can
be no moving forward without it".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rafu.com/2013/08/comfort-women-monument-unveiled-in-glendale/|title=Comfort Women Monument Unveiled in Glendale|first1=J. K. |last1=Yamamoto|first2=Mikey Hirano|last2=Culross|work=[[Rafu Shimpo]]|date=2 August 2013|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>

===Mayor===
In April 2014, Sinanyan was appointed mayor of Glendale, California replacing former mayor Dave Weaver.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zareh Sinanyan appointed mayor|url=http://articles.glendalenewspress.com/2014-04-09/news/tn-gnp-me-zareh-sinanyan-appointed-mayor-20140409_1_councilman-zareh-sinanyan-city-council-follow-brittany-levine|agency=Glendale News Press|date=9 April 2014}}</ref>

In November 2014 Sinanyan and Los Angeles mayor [[Eric Garcetti]] were among the California politicians invited to attend the opening of a [[BBCN]] representative office in [[Seoul]], South Korea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globenewswire.com/news-release/2014/11/25/686326/10109989/en/BBCN-Opens-Representative-Office-in-Seoul-Korea.html|title=BBCN Opens Representative Office in Seoul, Korea (press release)|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=17 December 2014|publisher=Globe Newswire}}</ref> Sinanyan also met with [[List of members of the National Assembly (South Korea), 2012<U+2013>|Lee Koon-hyon]], Secretary General of the [[Saenuri Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epa.eu/politics-photos/diplomacy-photos/glendale-mayor-zareh-sinanyan-in-seoul-photos-51675816|title=Glendale Mayor Zareh Sinanyan in Seoul|accessdate=17 December 2014|publisher=[[European Pressphoto Agency]]}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Sinanyan and his wife Lori have four children.<ref name=votez />

